post_text:
Seeking responses from residents of Windham and Tolland Counties!

Health Equity Solutions is collecting information to ensure that Connecticut’s COVID-19 response and recovery efforts include health equity.

The survey asks respondents to identify concerns and proposed solutions to those concerns. These results are shared with policymakers, other decision-makers, philanthropy, and Health Equity Solutions’ partners on a regular basis. The survey can be taken multiple times, and can be found here:

English Survey Link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/QN6BN3G
Spanish Survey Link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/HES_Spanish
Haitian-Creole Survey Link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/HES_Haitian-Creole

Summary results are available on their website and will be updated, http://hesct.org/covid-19/covid-19-health-equity-community-assessment-summary/.

Lastly, Health Equity Solutions is holding listening sessions, which can be found here: https://bit.ly/2RfLogR

post_text:
Marinho and Katiane (a married couple from Brazil) participated in our summer ESL online classes. Here is what they said about our virtual ESL program:

"Dynamic classes, with current topics that motivate discussion. The teachers are excellent--they allow the students to be comfortable for conversation and help them to overcome difficulties with the English language. In addition to conversational skills, there are also reading and grammar activities offered. EASTCONN also offers technological support, so that students have all the necessary tools and supports to learn a new language."

The Summer Youth Employment and Training Program is still accepting applications! This summer’s program will be a virtual training program for those 14-17 years old, and in person internships will be offered to most 18-24 years old (although they may opt for the virtual training instead). The participants get paid $11/hour for approximately 75-100 hours.

Space is limited so make sure you sign up today!

Announcing the launch of NeedAJobNow.usNLx.com, a job site dedicated to providing a centralized location for displaced workers to access employment opportunities from U.S. corporations with immediate hiring needs due to the novel coronavirus (COVID-19). The site houses jobs from vetted employers in all industries and provides an opportunity for Americans to return to work and gain meaningful employment. It contains over 400,000 job openings and continues to grow daily. While many employers are downsizing their staff, others are significantly increasing their hiring efforts due to current demands.

https://www.naswa.org/news/nlx-launches-job-resource-to-support-displaced-workers-during-pandemic

From our community partner Generations Family Health Center, here is a regularly updated list of COVID-19 test sites in Connecticut, including the sites that do pediatric testing:
https://www.genhealth.org/images/pdfs/2020/COVID_Testing.pdf

If you are starting to show COVID-19/Coronavirus symptoms, you need to reach out to your Primary Care Provider who will let you know if you should go to the ER or be tested. If your Provider says you should get tested you can refer to this guide to find a COVID-19 test site.

Please note that anyone getting tested should plan to bring their photo ID and insurance info if they have it. Most locations also require an order by a physician or nurse practitioner, and that the person being tested has fever, cough and/or shortness of breath in order to get the test. Test quantities are limited.

New Special Enrollment Period for Access Health CT

As the Coronavirus (COVID-19) continues to threaten public health, Access Health CT announced a NEW Special Enrollment Period for qualified uninsured Connecticut residents.

This Special Enrollment Period will be open from March 19 to April 2, 2020.

To see if you are eligible call 855-805-4325 (TTY: 1- 855-365-2428). Enrollment is available by phone only.

The Access Health call center will be helping people enroll Monday through Friday, from 8am to 5pm.

To learn more visit learn.accesshealthct.com.

post_text:
Comcast is offering 2 months free internet to low income families.
https://www.internetessentials.com/

Staying Connected During the Coronavirus Situation
As the country deals with the effects of the Coronavirus (COVID-19), Comcast is taking immediate steps to help connect more low-income families to the Internet at home. Effective Monday, March 16, 2020, anyone who signs up for Internet Essentials will receive two free months of Internet service. We are also increasing the speed of the program to 25 Mbps downloads, and 3 Mbps uploads for all new and existing customers.

After your first two free months expire, you can either cancel the service (which you can do at any time) or keep it as a regular paying Internet Essentials customer. You will receive an easy to use self-install-kit that includes a cable modem (to receive service at your home) with a WiFi router (to connect your devices without wires). There is no term contract or credit check and no shipping fee for equipment.
shared_text:
INTERNETESSENTIALS.COM
Internet Essentials from Comcast
text:
Comcast is offering 2 months free internet to low income families.
https://www.internetessentials.com/

Staying Connected During the Coronavirus Situation
As the country deals with the effects of the Coronavirus (COVID-19), Comcast is taking immediate steps to help connect more low-income families to the Internet at home. Effective Monday, March 16, 2020, anyone who signs up for Internet Essentials will receive two free months of Internet service. We are also increasing the speed of the program to 25 Mbps downloads, and 3 Mbps uploads for all new and existing customers.

After your first two free months expire, you can either cancel the service (which you can do at any time) or keep it as a regular paying Internet Essentials customer. You will receive an easy to use self-install-kit that includes a cable modem (to receive service at your home) with a WiFi router (to connect your devices without wires). There is no term contract or credit check and no shipping fee for equipment.

The Windham Tech boys soccer team extended its winning streak to three consecutive games following a victory Thursday afternoon over Goodwin Tech.
